rates_text1.html:
California's violent crime rate declined overall between 2007 and 2017.


California experienced a 14-percent decline in the violent crime rate between 2007 and 2017. However, since a 10-year low in 2014, the violent crime rate has increased each year. The violent crime rate did not decrease in all areas of the state between 2007 and 2017: while it decreased 15 percent in metropolitan areas, it increased 20 percent or more in micropolitan and non-metropolitan areas.

rates_text2.html:
• California's 26-percent decline in the homicide rate was the 5th-largest drop in the country between 2007 and 2017. The state went from having the 17th-highest homicide rate in the country in 2007 to the 28th highest in 2017.
  • Despite a 26-percent decline in the robbery rate, California had the 4th-highest rate of robberies in the country in 2017.
  • California was one of 21 states with a decline in the aggravated assault rate of more than 10 percent between 2007 and 2017. However, the rate of aggravated assaults in California in 2017 was still 6 percent higher than the U.S. rate of aggravated assaults.
